(1) This is a wrong question.

If two people have exactly the same scores for all 6 questions,
then the product of the scores for the 6 questions is the same, and the sum of the scores for the 6 questions is also the same;
thus, these two people have the same ranking, i.e., these two people are tied.
According to the problem, there are no ties among the $8^{6}=262144$ participants;
thus, the scores of the $8^{6}=262144$ participants for each question are not exactly the same.
The score for each question is an integer from $0 \sim 7$, and by the multiplication principle, there are $8^{6}$ possible score combinations;
if participant A's scores for questions $1 \sim 6$ are $0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1$, and participant B's scores for questions $1 \sim 6$ are $0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0$,
the product of the scores for the 6 questions for both A and B is 0, and the sum of the scores for the 6 questions is 1;
thus, A and B have the same ranking, i.e., these two people are tied;
