The reason is as follows:
If at least one of the 6 questions has a score of 0, then the product of the scores for the 6 questions is 0;
If none of the 6 questions has a score of 0, then the product of the scores for the 6 questions is not 0,
in this case, the score for each question is an integer from $1 \sim 7$, and by the multiplication principle, there are $7^{6}$ possible score combinations;
thus, the score of the participant ranked $7^{6}=117649$ is the smallest positive integer product;
and the participant whose scores for questions $1 \sim 6$ are $1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1$ has a score of 1;
thus, the score of the participant ranked $7^{6}=117649$ is 1 point.

